Learn more on our website: https://bit.ly/3blb4SP

post_text:
Kitty Hawk Elementary School Librarian Ellen Bryson has been named the 2020-21 Dare County Schools District Teacher of the Year. Ms. Bryson was chosen from among 10 other candidates. After earning a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Political and Social Issues from the University of Tennessee in 2001, Ms. Bryson joined AmeriCorps and taught elementary school in Cambridge, Massachusetts. She joined the Kitty Hawk Elementary Staff in 2007 as the school’s librarian. Ms. Bryson collaborates with other teachers to create an exciting and engaging experience when students visit the library. Her most recent work with students includes hosting a Wax Museum, and establishing a partnership with N.E.S.T. (Network of Endangered Sea Turtles) to promote environmental conservation on the Outer Banks.

Ms. Bryson will represent Dare County Schools and advance to the regional competition.

Kitty Hawk Elementary School
#daretolearn

shared_text:
Outer Banks Community Foundation
August 14 at 8:34 AM ·

Meet our 2020 R. Stewart Couch Scholar, Jadon Midgett. Jadon graduated from Cape Hatteras High School; he will attend Western Carolina University this fall. The R. Stewart Couch Memorial Scholarship for Hatteras Island, at $8,600, is our largest, single-year scholarship, and we congratulate Jadon, and all of our 2020 scholarship recipients, on their hard-earned awards.

Jadon wrote, “I have always felt inspired by the media and its impacts on our lives and society as a whole, particularly in the field of journalism. I would like to go into a journalism/communication related field and work for a major news network in the future, and believe that in this field I could help to improve our society as much as possible, with my contribution being through honest, genuine reporting and coverage of our nations’ top issues. I am applying to this scholarship because education has always been my top priority."

Jadon is passionate about connecting through Communications. What’s your passion? Find out how we help passionate people change the world at www.obcf.org.

DCS teachers have been working hard to prepare for the start of the 2020-21 school year! Let's kick things off with a Remote Learning Orientation beginning on August 17 for all students and families. Students and families will be able to access the orientation by visiting the DCS website.

On Monday, August 17, we will be posting teacher contact information on our website and all students will be able to spend the week learning how to use their teacher's chosen remote learning management system. We will also be sharing a video from each school principal and each DCS teacher.

The first day of new content instruction will be August 24.

Learn more by visiting our Remote Learning Website: https://bit.ly/3iBVdBE

post_text:
Governor Roy Cooper announced an Executive Order on March 14, 2020, that closes all North Carolina public schools for at least the next two weeks.

Starting on Monday, March 16, 2020, all Dare County Schools will be closed to students as directed by the Governor's Executive Order.

The Dare County Schools leadership team has developed a Remote Learning Plan to prepare for an event like this. We are prepared to begin a K-12 remote learning program that will commence this week.

Superintendent Farrelly will be communicating more details to parents, students, and staff by 2:00pm on Sunday, March 15.

We would like to thank Dare Education Foundation for making today's author visit possible. You may get signed books to you from the author at Downtown Books from 3:00-4:30. If you can not make that time, your student can stop by the library and get a form to turn in for a book signed by the author, just not personalized.

post_text:
A mandatory evacuation has been issued to all Dare County residents beginning on Wednesday, September 4 at 6:00 am.

As a result, Dare County Schools will be in regular session tomorrow, Tuesday, September 3, but will close for all students and staff beginning Wednesday, September 4 through Friday, September 6.

The Afterschool Enrichment Program (ASEP) will operate on a normal schedule tomorrow, Tuesday, September 3.

For hurricane preparedness tips and information, visit www.readync.org.

Subscribe to receive emergency alerts via text, email, or phone directly from Dare County Emergency Management at www.DareNC.com/alerts and follow @DareCountyEM on Twitter.

Monitor updated local weather forecasts from the National Weather Service at www.weather.gov/mhx.

Kitty Hawk Elementary School
March 7, 2019 at 11:45 AM ·

The NC PTA Reflections theme this year was “Heroes Around Me.” Congratulations to the following KHES winners:

Avery Stemple (K-2) Visual Arts - Momma
Colin Perrel (K-2) Visual Arts - Portrait of Ben
Noah Dondero (K-2) Visual Arts - Super Fruits and Veggies

Graham Baker (3-5) Music - We Can Be Heroes

Lily Casias (K-2) Literature - Lily’s Reflections
Will Britt (3-5) Literature - My Dad is the Best.

All of these talented students will be recognized at the Awards Ceremony at the end of the year. The KHES winners were sent to the state for judging and KHES had 3 State Winners this year!

Noah Dondero - 3rd Place (K-2) Visual Arts
Graham Baker - 3rd place (3-5) Music
Will Britt - 2nd place (3-5) Literature

Congratulations to everyone that participated!

post_text: Manteo Middle School recently completed a One School, One Book Project. Each student in the school read the book Restart. post_text: A creative way to encourage student advocacy! Great job students and thanks to Ms. Mount for providing this leadership opportunity! #daretolearn
shared_text:
Manteo High School
February 26, 2019 at 10:44 AM ·

After studying four techniques of satire in fiction, students in Kassie Mount's English 10 Honors class created their own satirical PSAs. Students were given the task of writing and performing a script that used exaggeration, parody, incongruity, or reversal to satirize a current social issue of their choice. Through this activity, students used creativity to voice their concern for issues such as low self-esteem, pollution, and impolite behavior.

post_text: Awesome! Great way to show leadership, Chloe! First Flight Elementary School #daretolearn
shared_text:
First Flight Elementary School is with Connie Barritt Grizzard at First Flight Elementary School.
February 1, 2019 at 5:20 PM · Kill Devil Hills, NC ·

Every "Thankful" Thursday my students get to write a letter to anyone in the whole world to let that person know he/she is thankful for them. A few weeks ago, Chloe Coleman, decided to write Cam Newton, the quarterback for the Carolina Panthers, since the Panthers are her and her Dad's favorite football team. I mailed the letter to the Cam Newton Foundation and Chloe received a package in the mail at FFES from them! The package contained a letter typed to Chloe stressing the importance of working hard in school to achieve her dreams, and she got a picture of Cam with his autograph on it! To make things even more exciting, the package also included a signed picture and another letter for the entire class to enjoy! I love that the letter included "Cam believes you can do anything you set your mind to, so dream big!"💗 What a great lesson for all! My first graders are learning how kind words and hand- written letters are truly appreciated by everyone! -Connie Grizzard
